Silver Spoon, the British granulated sugar brand is by far the biggest casualty of the backlash against sugar and its links to obesity.

The Grocer said: ‘A year ago, it was Britain’s 68th biggest grocery brand, but it has fallen out of the rankings with a staggering loss of £62.6m in sales – 47.1per cent – thanks partly to the sugar debate.’

It added: ‘The opprobrium surrounding the sugar levels in many grocery products has hit some players hard.’

The Cadbury brand – apart from Dairy Milk – has also suffered with sales down by 15.2per cent - £34.8m – in a year.

The giant has come under fire since a take-over by American food giant Kraft with concerns the new owners have failed to honour its British heritage.

It reneged on a promise to keep open a British factory, while consumers have complained about products being shrunk or changes to the chocolate used in products, such as the coating to its famous crème egg.

In the same category, Mars is down by 10.5per cent, while Kitkat has fallen some 7.6per cent. Just last week, the Mail revealed how its Kitkat chunky is less chunky after being cut from 48g to 40g without a corresponding fall in the price.

